/* Gender issues */ Clarification of Trottier comments in National Post
/* Gender issues */ Clarification of Trottier's interview in Metro News
/* Gender issues */ I count a couple dozen articles featuring Trottier that require quotations in order to achieve clarity. I have removed this one until I can add the others.

/* Gender issues */ Again, why are we quoting 3 lines from this particular article, while none of Trottier's other hundreds of articles merit this attention. Until this point is responded to, which I have made twice, I will continue to remove this
/* Gender issues */ removing references to articles that fail to mention Trottier
/* Gender issues */ This is more accurate, otherwise it reads as though all such groups oppose the Centre.

/* Gender issues */ The opposition is from feminist-oriented domestic violence groups. Many other domestic violence groups, like the Canadian Centre for Abuse Awareness and Gatehouse, support the Centre

/* Gender issues */ The group has been featured in over 400 articles, covering events, press releases, etc. To focus nearly all the attention here on controversies created by one magazine - NOW - is unbalanced
/* Gender issues */ "controversial men's rights" should be left up to the reader to decide and not used as an objective description of the organization.

/* Gender issues */ NOW's article on the charity application was sloppy and flawed. It failed to explain that the reference to feminist groups was part of the application asking for future program proposals.

/* Gender issues */ It makes no sense to quote Trottier from the article. He has been quoted in hundreds of articles. It is inconsistent with a fair accounting of his bio to single out one quote from one particular article
/* Canadian Centre for Men and Families */
Trottier is not a "long-time spokesperson" of CAFE. He is the director and spokesperson for the Canadian Centre for Men and Families, spelling correction
/* Events, Activities and Policies */ The word "however" suggests there is something inconsistent between the first and second sentence, which is open to debate. The paragraph should read neutrally
